Let’s be honest—when you think of pub snacks, your mind probably goes straight to the classics: peanuts, potato chips, maybe a bowl of pretzels or some greasy fries. But in recent years, a new contender has been quietly (and deliciously) climbing the ranks in European pubs: rye bread chips. Yep, those crunchy, garlicky slices of toasted goodness that are impossible to stop munching once you start. So how did this humble snack go from leftover bread to pub royalty? Grab a drink and let’s dive in.
From Leftovers to Legend
The story of rye bread chips starts, like many great food inventions, with one simple question: What do we do with all this old bread? In places like the Baltics and Eastern Europe, rye bread is a staple—dense, flavorful, and filling. But it also goes stale fast. Instead of tossing it, clever cooks started slicing it up, seasoning it with garlic, herbs, or cheese, and toasting or frying it until crispy.
Boom. Waste not, want not.
These crunchy bites were perfect for nibbling, easy to make, and, most importantly, ideal for soaking up beer—making them a natural fit for bars and pubs.
The Baltic Birthplace
If we had to pick a hometown for rye bread chips, Lithuania and Latvia would definitely be in the running. In fact, if you ever find yourself in a Baltic bar, you’re almost guaranteed to see a bowl of these dark, crispy chips sitting next to your pint. They’re usually slathered in garlic butter and served with a cheesy or creamy dipping sauce. You’ll probably finish the whole bowl before your drink’s halfway gone. No judgment.
They go by different names depending on where you are—kepta duona in Lithuania, rupjmaizes kārtojums in Latvia (though that’s more of a dessert version), and just “rye chips” or “bread snacks” in English-speaking menus. But no matter the name, the vibe is the same: salty, crunchy, and totally addictive.
A Hipster’s Dream Come True
Of course, it didn’t take long for the rest of Europe to catch on. With the rise of craft beer bars, gastropubs, and a general obsession with “elevated” snacks, rye bread chips were basically tailor-made for the modern food scene. They’ve got that perfect combo of rustic + trendy, and they pair like a dream with all those IPAs and stouts.
Suddenly, what used to be a clever way to use up stale bread became a featured menu item—with house-made aioli or fancy blue cheese dips, no less. Some places even bake their own rye loaves just to chip them up later. That’s dedication.
The Crunch Heard ‘Round the World
Now, you can find packaged versions of rye bread chips in grocery stores across Europe—and even in parts of the US. Brands have jumped on board, offering flavors like sour cream and onion, smoked cheese, and (of course) garlic. Some stay true to the original dense, dark rye. Others lighten things up a bit. Either way, it’s clear that these little guys have gone global.
So Why Do People Love Them So Much?
Honestly? It’s the crunch. Rye bread chips hit that magical intersection of hearty, salty, and satisfying. They don’t leave your fingers greasy, they actually feel kinda filling, and they just feel right with a cold beer. Whether you’re in a cozy pub in Riga, a hip beer bar in Berlin, or on your couch with a lager and a Netflix binge, rye bread chips are the snack you didn’t know you needed.
And now that you do—good luck stopping after just one.

